link:labelLink.link:label: BIS-OTC reporting dealers

Reporting dealers are those institutions whose head offices participate in the BIS's semiannual OTC derivatives market statistics and located in one of the 13 reporting countries. In addition, reporting dealers include all branches and subsidiaries of these entities worldwide.
OTC-REP-DLRS
Instrument bought/sold

Derivative instruments can be bought or sold. If an instrument is sold, the reporting institution is a writer of the derivative. If an instrument is bought, the reporting institution is a purchaser of the derivative.
INSTR-BS
Replacement value (sign)
Replacement values stand for the price to be received or paid if the instrument were sold in the market at the time of reporting, there are positive and negative replacement values.

The market on which a derivative is traded. A derivative can be traded over-the-counter (OTC) or on an exchange market.
MARKET

Remaining maturity

Remaining maturity of a derivative contract, the remaining maturity of each leg should be determined as the difference between the reporting date and the settlement or due date, respectively, of the near and far-end legs of the transaction.
REM-MAT
Market risk

Market risk is the risk of a price movement in the underlying of the derivative. Individual derivatives transactions are to be categorised into six risk classes: foreign exchange, single-currency interest rate, equity, commodity, credit and other.
